<span>1. The top 1% of earners pay 45.8% of the federal income taxes. (</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://x.com/Mark_J_Perry/status/1633114633853599750" rel=3D=
"">source</a><span>). I=E2=80=99m far from 1%, but I am learning the truth =
of that old adage about the government, =E2=80=9Cthe more you make, the mor=
e they take.=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99m fine with a progressive tax system. Still=
, one of the rare times I miss being poor is during tax season. I used to g=
et a few hundred or even a thousand bucks back. Now I send the money I owe =
and briefly contemplate jumping out a window.</span></p><p><span>2. The fam=
ous actor and martial artist Bruce Lee had a cocaine habit, cheated on his =
wife, and was found dead in his mistress's hotel room in 1973 (</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.thetimes.com/uk/society/article/enemy-bruce-lee-couldnt-k=
ick-his-drug-habit-fhjsps3pw" rel=3D"">source</a><span>). So often if you s=
cratch the surface any figure from the late 60s and early 70s, you find thi=
s pattern. Then people rewrite history to conceal the pervasive debauchery =
of that era. I=E2=80=99m curious to see how director Ang Lee is going to ap=
proach this in the </span><a href=3D"https://variety.com/2022/film/news/bru=
ce-lee-biopic-ang-lee-1235445696/" rel=3D"">upcoming Bruce Lee biopic</a><s=
pan>. &nbsp;</span></p><p><span>3. Correlations between spouses (</span><a =
href=3D"https://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/abs/10.1017/S0022381611000016=
" rel=3D"">source</a><span>)</span></p><p>Extraversion: r=3D .005</p><p>Neu=
roticism: .082</p><p>Height: .227</p><p>Weight: .154</p><p>Education: .5</p=
><p>Political party: .6</p><p>The researchers note that =E2=80=9CMates tend=
 to be positively but weakly concordant on personality and physical traits,=
 but concordance of political attitudes is extremely high.=E2=80=9D</p><p>P=
olitical orientation is a rough proxy for values. And education is a rough =
proxy for intelligence. People generally favor partners who are similar to =
themselves in terms of these two characteristics.</p><p><span>In his essay =
on hypergamy, Scott Alexander </span><a href=3D"https://www.astralcodexten.=
com/p/hypergamy-much-more-than-you-wanted" rel=3D"">writes</a><span>:</span=
></p><blockquote><p><em>=E2=80=9CI know many rich male Google programmers, =
but I have never seen any of them marry a stunning black girl from the ghet=
to. Why not? Wouldn=E2=80=99t the hypergamy hypothesis pronounce this a goo=
d deal for both of them? He gets a beautiful wife, she gets a rich husband?=
 And it=E2=80=99s not just a race thing, I=E2=80=99ve also never seen them =
marry a beautiful hillbilly from West Virginia, or a beautiful farmer=E2=80=
=99s daughter from Modesto. I don=E2=80=99t even really see them marry a be=
autiful girl from the suburbs with a community college degree.=E2=80=9D</em=
></p></blockquote><p><span>I=E2=80=99ve never seen anything like this eithe=
r. Research from Gregory Clark </span><a href=3D"https://press.princeton.ed=
u/books/hardcover/9780691162546/the-son-also-rises" rel=3D"">suggests</a><s=
pan> assortative mating (the trend whereby people choose spouses who are si=
milar to themselves not just in terms of appearance, but in terms of educat=
ion, intellect, and class background) has endured for centuries and hasn=E2=
=80=99t changed all that much. People point to the mid-twentieth century an=
d speak about male executives marrying their secretaries. But Clark=E2=80=
=99s work suggests that smarter executives tended to marry smarter secretar=
ies. In terms of occupational prestige, there was a gap. But underlying abi=
lities still drew people together. What=E2=80=99s on your resume doesn=E2=
=80=99t seem to matter as much as what=E2=80=99s in your head; though nowad=
ays, as social barriers have dissolved, those two things are more tightly c=
orrelated than before. People are pretty good at picking up on these invisi=
ble attributes when seeking a long-term partner. This is why I think males =
dropping out of higher ed won=E2=80=99t have much of an effect on assortati=
ve mating. Women can still detect a man=E2=80=99s intellect and overall com=
petence by relying on signals other than educational credentials. </span></=
p><p>For what it=E2=80=99s worth, I=E2=80=99ve noticed my own long-term rel=
ationship history reflects this assortative mating pattern along class line=
s: </p></div></div><div class=3D"visibility-check"></div><div class=3D"payw=
